    <div class="field field-name-field-page-tags field-type-taxonomy-term-reference field-label-hidden clearfix"><ul class="links"><li class="taxonomy-term-reference-0"><a href="/tags/drupal-7x" typeof="skos:Concept" property="rdfs:label skos:prefLabel" datatype="">drupal 7.x</a></li><li class="taxonomy-term-reference-1"><a href="/tags/drupalgap" typeof="skos:Concept" property="rdfs:label skos:prefLabel" datatype="">drupalgap</a></li><li class="taxonomy-term-reference-2"><a href="/tags/phonegap" typeof="skos:Concept" property="rdfs:label skos:prefLabel" datatype="">phonegap</a></li><li class="taxonomy-term-reference-3"><a href="/tags/planet-drupal" typeof="skos:Concept" property="rdfs:label skos:prefLabel" datatype="">planet drupal</a></li></ul></div><div class="field field-name-body field-type-text-with-summary field-label-hidden"><div class="field-items"><div class="field-item even" property="content:encoded"> <p>In this tutorial we'll explore how to make a simple mobile application game with <a href="http://www.drupalgap.org">DrupalGap</a> for a <a href="http://www.drupal.org">Drupal</a> 7 website. Our game will help us learn words in another langauge.</p><p>We'll use Drupal to manage our words and their translations. Since Drupal comes with a default content type called Article, we'll use that for our words.</p></div></div></div>
